A quick case study of the evaluation of a recent patient @seanmichaelcorsiglia who had been dealing with knee pain for 2 years. The main point of this post is that when addressing injuries, modifying and managing load is only 1 part of the solution. We just always assess and address imbalances in mechanics.
.
If you’re dealing with knee pain & want to learn about how to test and uncover your individual reason for pain, start with my YouTube video “4 tips for knee pain.”📲
.
Shout out to @seanmichaelcorsiglia for working hard to fix this issue & to @3d4medical with the Complete Anatomy app visual of the body in today’s video.

The stretch I'm demonstrating today is one of my favorite hip openers to use prior to squatting. It's a stretch I learned years ago from Kelly Starrett of @thereadystate. Keys for proper execution: keep your trail leg straight & lean from the hips (don't drop your chest as you lean forward). As always, test - retest to see if this mobility exercise is right for you! Sit into a deep squat. Notice how you feel. Then perform this stretch - and immediately sit into your squat after. If you felt like you could sit more comfortably in the deep squat position - this stretch was efficient for your body to help you get into better positions! 
.
To learn more of my other favorite hip mobility exercises, check out my YouTube video “Hip Mobility for a Perfect Squat.”📲
.
Shout out to @epiersonproductions for the awesome videographer skills in making this video🙏🏼

node.text:
Today I want to show you why finding your individual movement diagnosis for shoulder pain is so important. Jerome came to me with shoulder pain when snatching - now traditional medial model will try to look at a scan of your shoulder and determine what they see as “abnormal” to be the exact cause of pain. In Jerome’s case they found a small tear in his labrum. However, abnormal findings on MRI do not always equal the exact cause of prin. In fact there is a lot of science to show people have these abnormal findings without any pain. One in particular showed close to 80% of major league pitchers had a labrum abnormality without pain! 
.
So what do we do when an athlete presents with pain? We don’t just try random exercises we see on social media – as there is no “one size fits all” approach for fixing injury. What we do is evaluate and assess to uncover the exact path to take.
.
If you’re dealing with shoulder issues & want to try some of the tests I use to figure out what to do next, start with my blog “How to screen your shoulder pain” on squatuniversity.com📲

The traditional medical model will try to look at a scan of your back and determine what they see as “abnormal” to be the exact cause of pain. However, there is a ton of research that shows just because you find a problem on MRI does not mean it’s the exact cause of pain. 
.
So what do we do?  We fit your symptoms into a movement diagnosis category! This is something I learned from renowned back expert @backfitpro. A movement diagnosis tells you what motions, postures and loads to avoid in the short term so we don’t continue your pain. It doesn’t matter how many corrective exercises or stability drills you do, if you continue to push into your trigger for pain, it usually won’t get better on it’s own. 
.
The process of limiting individual movement triggers has been shown in research to help reduce pain effectively. It’s not creating fear of movement but rather empowering you to understand your injury so you can take control of the rehab process. 
.
Shout out to @krispy_kremez for being my patient model in this video!

Lat flexibility is key for overhead lifting. If you’re struggling with any lifting overhead, try this test I showed @martinslicis. If you come up short & specifically have worse mobility with your palms up (an externally rotated shoulder position) try the lat stretch I showed. After a few reps of 10 second holds you can see a huge change for his mobility. This has been a steady part of his routine the past year as he works out of injury & back to competition mode!!! 
.
If you’d like to learn more about lat flexibility drills, check on t my blog article “How to improve lat and pec flexibility” on SquatUniversity.com📲
.
Shout out to @martinslicis for the hard work & @romarkweiss for filming our collaboration work!

node.text:
What are your thoughts?🤔 The idea is that if you’re constantly comparing you lifts to others, it’s easy to try and rush the process.  Sure when you’re a competitive athlete it’s important to know where your competition stands, but dwelling on the comparison shifts your mindset off what YOU can control. Focus your energy/time on what YOU want to accomplish & execute…trust the process and good things will happen.

node.text:
Some people reference technique problems as an “energy leak,” but what does that really mean?🤔
.
The body is often referred to as a kinetic chain, as everything from the head to the feet must work together in a coordinated fashion to accomplish the set task. When you squat, it’s not just your quads doing the work but the entire body.🏋🏼‍♀️
.
If there’s an imbalance anywhere along the chain in creating tension and generating force, energy is dissipated into a different task breaking the chain and making the overall movement less efficient. This also creates microtrauma as certain tissues are now overloaded that could eventual lead to injury.🥊
.
Think about it like this, if I throw a baseball at a wall. The balls structure remains in tact and the energy from the ball hitting the wall creates an equal reaction in making the ball bounce back. However, if I throw a ball of spaghetti at the wall, the structure of the original ball deforms as it hits the wall. The energy is dissipated and the spaghetti does not bounce back.🤾🏽‍♂️
.
This is why working to fix technique problems improves your lifting efficiency, allowing your to maintain energy into the desired task so you can move big weight with less risk from movement related injuries🙌🏼
.
Shout out to @oc_lifting for being today’s athlete model, to @3d4medical with the Complete Anatomy app for the visual of the body🙏🏼

node.text:
So your workout today includes pistol squats, but you can’t do this without falling over. Many coaches in this case will have their athletes grab some rings or handles of a suspension trainer and use the ropes to assist in achieving a full pistol squat. But what if I told you this isn’t the best alternative?🤯
. 
What makes a pistol squat so challenging is the combination of great mobility AND stability to not only drop down but get back up. By grabbing the rings and assisting your single leg squat you completely take away the need to create stability. You’re also decreasing the demand on mobility in order to reach the bottom position by holding onto the straps. Sure you may be able to squat deeper, but doing so isn’t going to help carry over to a better single leg squat once the bands are taken away.❌
. 
Instead, grab a small plate and perform a touch down squat. Start off with a small hinge and squat down until you gently tap your heel to the ground before coming back up. As this gets easier to perform you can build up the height by adding more plates or even going to a box eventually. Then if you think you’re ready for a pistol, slowly bring your free leg forward as you descend to a greater depth.✅
. 
If you need help with ankle mobility, you can simultaneously work on that with exercises like the box ankle stretch. While you may not be going as deep, the touchdown squat will provide a greater training stimulus for improving stability and functional use of the mobility you have in a way that will better carry over to your other lifts like cleans or squats.🏋🏼‍♂️
.
To learn more about the pistol squat progression I teach, check out my YouTube video “How to Get Your First Pistol”📲

node.text:
Being “rooted” means to have a solid connection with the ground in order to establish a firm foundation for your body to move on top of. Too often the shoes we wear hinder optimal foot function and limit our ability to effectively establish this foundation. 
.
This is why I’m such a big fan of barefoot lifting for certain lifts (as you can really expose and solidify that rooted position) and then using shoes with a wide toe box that allow you to express that same connection in instances where you have to wear shoes (such as in certain gyms that don’t allow barefoot or with certain lifts that are performed better with a shoe). 
.
The shoe Martins is lifting in (@bearfootshoes) is just one excellent example of a shoe that does LESS TO the foot and therefore is better FOR the foot and it’s ability to function optimally. 
.
If you’re serious about your performance & technique quality, you need to be serious about how your foot is functioning.
